The accurate characterization of energy dissipation in physical systems is often confounded by measurement noise, which can introduce a persistent energy floor that obscures the true decay dynamics. This study presents a framework to correct for this noise-induced bias in a dataset of 20 simulated damped harmonic oscillators. We isolate and characterize the noise by analyzing the late-time signal (t > 15s), where the physical motion is negligible, to empirically calculate the variance of the displacement and velocity measurements for each oscillator. From these variances, a constant energy bias term is derived and subtracted from the total measured energy, yielding a corrected energy trajectory. To validate the method, we perform a non-linear least-squares fit of an exponential decay model to the corrected energy curves to extract the observed damping rates. The results demonstrate that the correction successfully removes the artificial energy floor, and the recovered damping rates show strong agreement with the known theoretical values, with a mean residual close to zero across all oscillators. This methodology provides a robust approach for recovering underlying physical dissipation rates from noisy data, proving especially effective in systems with low signal-to-noise ratios.

